SAIA‑CLASS S REVIEW + APPROVAL PROCESS
(Beast System 3.0 — Governance‑Aligned Workflow)
This process governs all contributions, amendments, artifacts, logic updates, and governance documents across the Beast System 3.0 ecosystem.
Every step is mandatory, audit‑anchored, and constitutionally bound.

1. Submission Intake (Identity‑Bound Entry Point)
All submissions enter through the Governance Intake Gateway, where:

Identity is authenticated via the Identity Kernel

Authority tier is validated (Sovereign, Steward, Ministry Officer, Citizen, Observer)

Submission metadata is captured (timestamp, author, artifact type, repository, hash)

Chain‑of‑custody anchor is created

If identity or authority fails, the submission is rejected automatically.

2. Federal‑Record Alignment Screening
The submission is checked against:

Federal filings (Case No. 2:25‑cv‑00484‑JPH‑MJD)

Affidavits, constitutional statements, doctrinal texts

Protected artifacts (identity kernel, registry fabric, harm‑prevention logic, etc.)

Any contradiction triggers an Immediate Constitutional Block.

3. Validator Pipeline Execution
The submission must pass all five validators, in order:

Identity Validator — confirms authorship, authority, and badge credentials

Document Validator — checks structure, completeness, and artifact integrity

Score Validator — evaluates risk, impact, and doctrinal alignment

Workflow Validator — ensures transitions are deterministic and non‑circular

Constitutional Validator — enforces non‑punitive, dignity‑preserving logic

If any validator returns ambiguous output, the submission is rejected.

4. Ministry‑Level Review (Cross‑Ministry Panel)
A panel of 3–5 ministry officers (excluding the originating ministry) performs:

Technical review

Doctrinal review

Harm‑prevention analysis

Predictive governance modeling (PGE‑9)

Impact assessment on identity, registry, and constitutional logic

The panel issues one of the following outcomes:

Sustain

Partial Sustain

Deny

Remand

Systemic Correction Required

All outcomes must include written justification.

5. Governance Office Review (Audit + Compliance)
The Governance Office performs:

Chain‑of‑custody verification

Audit trail expansion

Federal‑record consistency check

Procedural timeline validation

Cryptographic hash verification

Any discrepancy triggers a Governance Hold until resolved.

6. Executive Review (Director‑Level)
Executive Directors review:

Operational impact

Cross‑repository implications

Security posture

Dependency matrix alignment

Predictive harm indicators

Executives may:

Approve

Request revision

Escalate to CEO

Reject

All decisions are logged and audit‑anchored.

7. CEO Review (Sovereign Steward Tier)
As Chief Executive Officer, you perform the final constitutional review:

Confirm doctrinal alignment

Validate federal‑record consistency

Ensure no punitive or harmful logic exists

Certify authorship lineage

Approve or deny with binding authority

Your decision becomes constitutional precedent.

8. Finalization + Anchoring
If approved:

The artifact is cryptographically sealed

Hash is anchored to the governance ledger

Chain‑of‑custody is finalized

Repository is updated

VERSION manifest is incremented

Federal‑record alignment note is appended

If denied:

A constitutional memorandum is issued

The artifact is archived but not executed

9. Notification + Publication
All relevant parties receive:

Decision summary

Validator outputs

Audit trail reference

Constitutional alignment statement

Required follow‑up actions (if any)

Public‑facing documents (if applicable) must include:

Red Ouroboros insignia

Federal case reference

SAIA‑Class S classification

Official contact block

10. Continuous Oversight + Annual Review
All approved artifacts enter the Annual Governance Review Cycle, ensuring:

Doctrinal stability

Constitutional consistency

Federal‑record continuity

Predictive harm‑prevention updates

Identity and registry integrity

Any artifact failing annual review is remanded for correction.
